Forum App (NodeJS)

20 steps

We're about to embark on an exciting journey into the world of building a feature-rich forum application. This application will empower users to engage in discussions by creating posts, and they can also interact by leaving comments on these posts.

Building this application will serve as a culmination of the knowledge and skills we have gained throughout our campaign, particularly the concepts of Routes and Controllers. We will once again leverage the power of MongoDB, a NoSQL database, to store and manage the data generated by our Forums.

To organize this data effectively, we'll create three new collections: "User," "Post," and "Comments."

Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

NodeJS

Learning Outcomes

By the end of your learning, you will be able to

  • Develop a real-world Forums application, a common use case in web development
  • Create and manage three distinct collections: "User," "Post," and "Comments" to handle different data types.
  • Describe the relationship between posts and comments within the application's data structure
  • Map application functionality to specific routes and control logic using controllers

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 20

  • Step 1: Setting Up Our Workspace

    To start, open a coding workspace of your choice such as VS Code. Open your terminal in your code editor and ensure that the current working directory is the root folder StackUp-BackEnd-ExpressJS-Part-II.

    Next, enter the following commands in your terminal.

    mkdir forum-app
cd forum-app
npm install bcryptjs body-parser dotenv ejs express express-session mongoose

    In the code above, there are 3 commands. First, mkdir creates a new folder. The next command changes the current working directory to the new folder we have created. The last command will install the following 7 packages: bcryptjs, body-parser, dotenv, ejs, express, express-session, and mongoose.

  • Step 2: Project Setup

    Before we continue, let us create the folders and files we need for this project. Within your project folder forum-app, we are going to create a new folder called models. It will be the folder that will store the schemas of our database. For this project, we will be using a Non-Relational Database called MongoDB. It is a NoSQL Database.

    Next, in the same project folder, create a folder called views and another folder called public. These folders are for the EJS files that we will be creating in later steps. The public folder will contain all the files needed that are publicly accessible by the users of the web application. The views folder will contain the EJS files that will be server-rendered to the front end.

    Next, in the same project folder, create 2 more folders, routes and controllers. These 2 folders will be where we place the subroutes and application logic.

    By now, if you have done the workspace and project setup correctly, your project folder forum-app should have six folders models, node_modules, public, routes, controllers and views, and two JSON files - package-lock.json and package.json.

    For any JavaScript project, it is important to have your package.json file as it is crucial in storing the dependencies you have used in any project. The package-lock.json file is an intermediary file that is optional to keep.

  • Step 3: Environment Variables

    Next, within the project folder, create a new file .env. This file will be where we can store sensitive information like API Keys, Application Secrets, Database connections and more. It is a recommended practice for developers to adhere to this convention as .env files are usually used on a local level. Though the credentials and information are stored in plain text, usually .env files will be ignored by Git and will not be stored in a version source control service (VCS) like GitHub or GitLab. This reduces the risk of you having sensitive information uploaded onto a public GitHub repository.

    Now, copy the code below and add it to the .env file.

    db_connection="to_be_added_in_subsequent_steps"
PORT=3001
    Plain text

    In the code above, we defined our port number to be 3001. Port numbers can be any number within the range of 1 to 65535. Only one application can use a specific port at any point in time. As long as the port is free, your NodeJS application can use it and listen for any incoming requests. However, there are some restrictions and conventions you will need to adhere to. Just to name a few, ports 80 and 443 are reserved for HTTP requests, port 22 is for Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) connections and port 21 is for File Transfer Protocol (FTP).

    We will be using the .env file to store our application port number and our database connection string. You can think of this file as an Environment Configuration. In software development, when deploying our applications to servers, sometimes our application might change different variables that run the application, like different database credentials, port numbers and more. .env files will be applied locally on the device where the file is placed.

    Next, you might be wondering how we are going to use these variables in our JavaScript files. In Step 1, we installed a package called dotenv. It is a JavaScript package that will do the necessary heavy lifting in managing and storing these variables, making it accessible to us in the JavaScript files. In Step 12, we will import it. That is when you will be able to use the environmental variables as stored.

  • Step 4: Reusable components in EJS

    We will be creating a server-rendered web application using EJS as the View Engine. EJS is Embedded JavaScript and it will be a way for us to create a templated frontend view using HTML and CSS as the foundation. We can dynamically import and change the content shown within the EJS views as well.

    Similar to ReactJS, NextJS and other Front End Framework, we can create reuseable components. To create a reusable component, within the views folder, create a new folder called components. This will be the folder where we store all the various components we want to reuse in our EJS.

    In the components folder, create a new file called header.ejs. Then, add the following code below. 

    <nav class="navbar">
    <div class="row split align-center w-100">
        <a href="/dashboard" style="color: white; font-size: 30px;">Forums</a>
        <% if(username){ %>
            <ul>
                <li><a class="nav-link" href="/post">Post</a></li>
            </ul>
            <% } else { %>
                <div class="row gap-10">
                    <a class="nav-link" href="/auth/login">Login</a>
                    <a class="nav-link" href="/auth/register">Register</a>
                </div>
                <% } %>
    </div>
</nav>
    HTML

    You will notice that we are not starting off with the <head> element or the <html> tag. This is because this element will be added on top of another EJS file which will contain the necessary <html> and <head> elements.

    This is the application header that will show 2 types of views. When the user is logged in, it will show the Post navigation (line 6). When the user is not logged in, it will show the buttons, Login and Register (lines 10 and 11).

    Using the <% %> EJS tags, we are able to add JavaScript code within them. You can see similar usage in lines 4, 8 and 13. Together, they form a JavaScript selection statement that checks if the username is not undefined. If the username is defined, it will show the link for Post (line 6). Otherwise, it will show links to login and register (lines 10 and 11).

  • Step 5: index.ejs

    Within the views folder, create a new file called index.ejs. Within this file, add the code shown below.

    <!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/styles.css">
    <title>Welcome</title>
</head>

<body>
    <%- include('components/header',{username:username?username:""}) %>
        <div class="container">
            <h1>Welcome to the Forum!</h1>
            <p>Please <a href="/auth/register">Register</a> or <a href="/auth/login">Login</a> to continue.</p>
        </div>
</body>

</html>
    HTML

    The view engine processes a template file, like index.ejs, through an "ingestion" phase. During ingestion, it replaces variables in the EJS file with corresponding HTML elements. After completing the ingestion, it sends the converted HTML file to the user's browser.

    In line 12, we will use the <%- %> tag to include the header file we have created in the previous step. We will use a ternary operator to add in username and parse it into the header file. A ternary operator is just like an If statement but written in a single line.

        </div>
</body>

</html>
    HTML

    This file will provide a login interface for users. Similar to index.ejs, the page includes a header component (line 12). This is achieved through the EJS template engine's include function, which inserts the content of the 'components/header' template file into this spot.

    The form sends a POST request to the "/auth/login" URL when submitted with the username and password (line 15). If the user has yet to create their password, they can be redirected to create their account (line 24).

                        <%= post.title %>
                    </h4>

                        <%= post.content %>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <!-- Form to post a new comment -->

                </form>
                <!-- Comments -->
                <div style="margin-top: 10px;">
                    <% comments?.forEach(comment=>{ %>
                        <div class="comment">

                        </div>

            </div>
</body>

</html>
    HTML

    This file will display a forum post with comments. The post's title and content are dynamically populated from the post object's title (line 15) and content attributes (line 18). A <form> element allows other users to make comments on the post (lines 22 to 27). Once they click the 'Post Comment' button (line 26), they will make a POST request to /post/comment/id/:post_id. We will also use the forEach() function to iterate through the comments array and display the various comments the users have made (lines 30 to 33).

  • Step 12: App.js and Routings

    Now, we will need to create the main entry file for our back end application. Within the project folder, forum-app, create a new file called app.js and add the following code.

    require('dotenv').config();
const express = require('express');
const mongoose = require('mongoose');
const session = require('express-session');
const bcrypt = require('bcryptjs');
const User = require('./models/UserModel');

const app = express();
const port = process.env.PORT || 3001;

mongoose.connect(process.env.db_connection, {
    useNewUrlParser: true,
    useUnifiedTopology: true,
});

app.set('view engine', 'ejs');
app.use(express.static('public'));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true }));

app.use(session({
    secret: process.env.SESSION_SECRET,
    resave: false,
    saveUninitialized: false
}));

// Routes

app.use("/auth", require("./routes/authHandling"));
app.use("/post", require("./routes/postHandling"));
app.use('/', require('./routes/indexHandling'));

const server = app.listen(port, () => {
    console.log("Server listening");
    mongoose.connect(process.env.db_connection).then(() => {
        console.log("Database Connected");
    });
});
    JavaScript

    You might recall in Step 3 that we used the .env file to store our environment variables. We will import the module to this file (line 1). Then, we use the environment variable (process.env.db_connection) to connect to our database (line 11). We will be using MongoDB. We will touch more on databases in the subsequent steps.

    Next from lines 16 to 18, we will apply the various middlewares which are essentially the configurations we need to set up our back end. We will set the current view engine to EJS (line 16). We set the public folder by referencing the path in relation to app.js (line 17). Finally, we define how Express will receive and configure the incoming request, such that we will be able to use JSON to obtain the data we have received from the client (line 18).

    Lines 28 to 30 represent our primary routes. Previously, we touched on primary routings, sub-routes and controllers. API endpoints are URL and URL parameters that the client can contact the back end. When creating a URL string, you might want to consider the various requirements.

    Referring to lines 32 to 37, we will first connect to our database using our database connection string in our environment variables. Once we have connected to our database, we will start listening for any incoming messages to our back-end application (line 32). Since we have yet to set up our database, we are unable to connect to the database yet.

    We created 3 primary routes: /auth, /post, and /. These will be further linked to the subroutes in the routes folder.

    Do note that HTML form data does not support any other HTML methods except for GET and POST requests. If we are using the native JavaScript fetch() module, we can use other HTML methods like PUT, DELETE and PATCH. Frontend framework like ReactJS and NextJS will have fetch() preinstalled.

  • Step 13: Route Handling

    Within the routes folder, create a new file authHandling.js and add the code shown below. 

    const router = require('express').Router();
const authController = require('../controllers/authController');

// Views
router.get('/register', (req,res)=> authController.registerView(req,res));
router.get('/login', (req,res)=> authController.loginView(req,res));

router.post('/register', (req, res) => authController.register(req, res));
router.post('/login', (req, res) => authController.login(req, res));

module.exports = router;
    JavaScript

    In the code above, we will define the various sub-routes that belong to /auth such as registering and logging in. Each route shown will be directed to its respective functions in the authController file. These 2 routes will be linked to the authController.js that we will be creating in subsequent steps. It will be responsible for handling the user authentication, access and actions.

Since this is a Server Side Rendering application, the routes request to retrieve information and render the views will be routed through the same server. As such, we want to have a handler to organise the API routes that is responsible for rendering the pages.

  • Step 14: Controllers

    We will now add the logic part of our forum application.

    Within the controllers folder, create a new file called indexController.js and add the code below.

    const CommentModel = require("../models/CommentModel");
const PostModel = require("../models/PostModel");

const indexView = async (req, res) => {
    try {
        res.status(200).render('index',{
            username: req.session.username
        })
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).send({
            message: error.message
        })
    }
}

const dashboardView = async (req, res) => {
    try {
        if (!req.session.userId) {
            return res.redirect('/auth/login');
        }

        let post = await PostModel.find().then((posts) => posts);
        res.status(200).render('dashboard', {
            username: req.session.username,
            posts: post
        });
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).send({
            message: error.message
        })
    }
}

const postView = async (req, res) => {
    try {
        res.status(200).render('post',{
            username: req.session.username
        })
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).send({
            message: error.message
        })
    }
}

const postViewById = async (req, res) => {
    try {
        let post = await PostModel.findById(req.params.id).then((post) => post);
        let comments = await CommentModel.find({ post_id: req.params.id }).then((comments) => comments);
        res.render('post_id', {
            username: req.session.username,
            post: post,
            comments: comments
        })
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).send({
            message: error.message
        })
    }
}

module.exports = {
    indexView,
    dashboardView,
    postView,
    postViewById,
}
    JavaScript

    We first import the necessary models for "Comment" and "Post". Do note that these files will be created in the next step. Next, we define the indexView controller (line 4). This controller is responsible for rendering the index EJS view. It sets the username variable in the rendered view context based on the req.session.username (line 7). If rendering is successful, it sends a 200 response. If an error occurs during rendering, it sends a 500 (Internal Server Error) response with an error message.

    We then define the dashboardView controller (lines 16 to 32). This controller renders the dashboard view, typically representing a user's dashboard. It first checks if a user is authenticated by verifying the presence of req.session.userId (line 18). If not authenticated, it redirects the user to the /auth/login page. If authenticated, it retrieves a list of posts using PostModel.find() (line 22) and then renders the dashboard view with the username and the posts data. If there's an error during rendering or data retrieval, it sends a 500 response with an error message.

    We create the postViewById controller which renders the post_id view (line 50) and displays the details of a specific post. It first fetches the post using PostModel.findById() (line 48) based on the req.params.id and retrieves comments related to that post using CommentModel.find() (line 49). Then, it renders the post_id view with the username, post, and comments data. If there is an error during rendering or data retrieval, it sends a 500 response with an error message.

    .

    Next in the controllers folder, create another file called authController.js and add the code shown below. 

    const UserModel = require("../models/UserModel")
const bcrypt = require('bcryptjs');

const registerView = async (req, res) => {
    try {
        res.render('register');
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).send({
            message: error.message
        })
    }
}

const loginView = async (req, res) => {
    try {
        res.render('login');
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).send({
            message: error.message
        })
    }
}

const register = async (req, res) => {
    try {
        const { username, password } = req.body;
        const hashedPassword = await bcrypt.hash(password, 10);

        const user = new UserModel({
            username,
            password: hashedPassword
        });

        await user.save();

        res.redirect('/auth/login');
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).send({
            message: error.message
        })
    }
}

const login = async (req, res) => {
    try {
        const { username, password } = req.body;

        const user = await UserModel.findOne({ username });

        if (user && await bcrypt.compare(password, user.password)) {
            req.session.userId = user._id;
            req.session.username = user.username;

            return res.redirect('/dashboard');
        }

        res.redirect('/auth/login');
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).send({
            message: error.message
        })
    }
}

module.exports = {
    registerView,
    loginView,
    register,
    login
}
    JavaScript

    In the first 2 lines of the file, we import the necessary modules, including the UserModel (created in the next step) and the bcryptjs library for hashing passwords.

    Then, we define the registerView controller (line 4). This function is responsible for rendering the register view, a registration form for new users. It handles any potential errors during rendering, returning a 500 (Internal Server Error) response with an error message. The same logic applies for the loginView controller which renders the login view (lines 14 to 22).

    We define the register controller (line 24). This function handles the registration process when a user submits a registration form. It first extracts the username and password from the request body (line 26), then hashes the password using bcrypt. Next, it creates a new user instance using the UserModel, incorporating the username and hashed password. The user is saved to the database (line 34), and upon successful registration, the user is redirected to the login page (line 36).

    A note on storing user's passwords safely: When a user creates a new account, we parse the password through a hashing algorithm which will give us a unique string of letters that is then stored in our database. When the user logs in again with the same password, the same text is parsed through the same hashing algorithm. If the hashed string matches the one stored in the database, we can verify and let the request proceed to the next action. This is such that during an unfortunate data breach, malicious hackers will not be able to gain access to their accounts because the passwords stored are nothing but meaningless strings.
    -

    The login controller handles the login process when a user submits a login form (line 44). It extracts the username and password from the request body (line 46) and queries the database to find a user with a matching username using UserModel.findOne({ username }) (line 48). If a user is found and the provided password matches the stored hashed password using bcrypt.compare(), the user's session is initialized with their user ID and username, and they are redirected to the dashboard (line 54). If the login is unsuccessful, the user is redirected to the login page (line 57).

    .

    In the controllers folder, create a new file called postController.js and add the code shown below.

    const CommentModel = require("../models/CommentModel");
const PostModel = require("../models/PostModel");

const create_post = async (req, res) => {
    try {
        let { title, content } = req.body;
        let post = new PostModel({
            title,
            content,
            user_id: req.session.userId
        });

        await post.save();

        return res.redirect('/dashboard');
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).send({
            message: error.message
        })
    }
}

const submit_comment = async (req, res) => {
    try {
        let { comment } = req.body;
        let commentObj = {
            comment,
            user_id: req.session.userId,
            post_id: req.params.post_id
        }

        let commentModel = new CommentModel(commentObj);
        await commentModel.save();
        return res.redirect(`/post/${req.params.post_id}`);
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).send({
            message: error.message
        })
    }
}

module.exports = {
    create_post,
    submit_comment,
}
    JavaScript

    We define the create_post controller which handles the creation of new posts (line 4). It extracts the title and content of the post from the request body (line 6). It then creates a new PostModel instance (line 7) with the provided data, along with the user's user_id from the session. The post is saved to the database (line 13). Upon successful post creation, the user is redirected to the dashboard (line 15).

    We define the submit_comment controller which will handle the submission of comments on a post (line 23). It extracts the comment from the request body and assembles a commentObj (line 26) that includes the comment text, the user's user_id from the session, and the post_id from the URL parameters (assuming it identifies the post being commented on). A new CommentModel instance (line 32) is created with this commentObj, and it is saved to the database (line 33).

    After successful comment submission, the user is redirected to the specific post page using the req.params.post_id to construct the URL ("/post/{post_id}") (line 34).

  • Step 15: Models and Database

    Previously, we learnt how we can store data in our databases. We will use MongoDB which stores their data in JSON documents in an unstructured manner. Each new data is called a document. The documents are stored in a collection. Even though NoSQL databases are unstructured, we are able to provide structure templating to our MongoDB by specifying the schema.

    Now, within the models folder, create a new file called CommentModel.js and add the code shown below. 

    const mongoose = require('mongoose');

const commentSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
    comment: {
        type: String,
        required: true
    },
    user_id: {
        type: String,
        required: true
    },
    post_id: {
        type: String,
        required: true
    },
    upvotes: {
        type: Array,
        default: []
    },
    downvotes: {
        type: Array,
        default: []
    },
});

module.exports = mongoose.model('Comment', commentSchema);
    JavaScript

    We import mongoose, which is an Object Relational Mapping (ORM) module to communicate directly to our database (line 1).

    A note on communicating with databases: There are alternatives to communicating with databases. These can come in the form of raw query strings. The code below is a query string for SQL databases. This includes MySQL and MongoDB.

    SELECT * FROM tasks

    The reason why ORMs are better than writing query strings is that they are safer and a recommended practice in software development. Writing raw query strings poses a security concern and a huge risk to SQL injection. SQL injection is the name of a process when someone tries to inject another SQL string with the intent to steal or destroy databases and collections. Gone are the days when we will need to learn Query Languages. But it is still important that we learn the foundations of query strings as a programmer. If you are interested in reading more about SQL injection, please read this article.

    We define the keys that we are expecting to store in the database (line 3), such as comment (line 4) and user_id (line 8). Then, using the required property, we configure whether this key is necessary when creating a new document. If the key is not found within the document creation operation, the process of creating a new document will fail. It is similar to how MySQL checks for non-null values in the columns.

    .

    In the models folder, create a new file called PostModel.js and add the code shown below. 

    const mongoose = require('mongoose');

const postSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  title: {
    type: String,
    required: true
  },
  content: {
    type: String,
    required: true
  },
  user_id: {
    type: String,
    required: true
  }
});

module.exports = mongoose.model('Post', postSchema);
    JavaScript

    The logic works the same as CommentModel but in this case, we are specifying different keys to store in our document such as title and content.

    .

    In the models folder, create a new file called UserModel.js. Add the following code to the file you have just created. 

    const mongoose = require('mongoose');

const userSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  username: {
    type: String,
    required: true
  },
  password: {
    type: String,
    required: true
  }
});

module.exports = mongoose.model('User', userSchema);
    JavaScript

    In this file, we specify the keys username and password to be stored in our document. Both keys will be a String datatype. We will not be storing plain text passwords as it is an unsafe practice. Instead, we will only store the salted version of the password.

    Salting is the act of adding a series of random characters to a password before going through the hashing function. This is such that when there is a data breach, malicious users will not be able to gain access to the system without knowing the salt algorithm.

    For our Express session, we will also need a session secret. In the .env file, add the line:

    SESSION_SECRET="topsecret"
    Plain text

    SESSION_SECRET is used whenever the user has logged in. Whenever a user first logs in, we will use this session secret to append to the login request and for each request made by the same user, we can verify that this user was authenticated previously. In larger development teams, they might switch their authentication system to allow more dynamic usage. For example, they will rotate the session secret regularly to prevent malicious users.

  • Step 19: Troubleshooting Database Connections (Optional) 
    MongooseServerSelectionError: Could not connect to any servers in your MongoDB Atlas cluster. One common reason is that you're trying to access the database from an IP that isn't whitelisted. Make sure your current IP address is on your Atlas cluster's IP whitelist: https://www.mongodb.com/docs/atlas/security-whitelist/
    MongoNetworkError:... SSL routines:ss13_read_bytes:tlsv1 alert internal error

    Other symptoms: When you try to register for an account on the forum, nothing happens.

    Sometimes, you will not be able to connect to the database. This is because MongoDB will whitelist the IP Address that was used to create the database. As such, only the connection from that IP Address can be connected to the database.

    To whitelist your new IP Address, open up MongoDB Atlas Dashboard and select the Network Access that is shown on the side navigation panel.

    Click on the Add IP Address button. You will then need to enter your IP address in the Access List Entry field. Then, click on Confirm. You should then see your IP address added to the IP Access List. Restart your application and try connecting again.

    If you are using a cloud development environment like Gitpod, Codespaces or Google Cloud Shell and are not sure what IP address they are using, you can also temporarily use the Allow Access from Anywhere option. Do note that you are strongly discouraged from using the Allow Access from Anywhere as it is an unsafe security practice. This will allow anyone using the same db_connection string, from the .env file, to access the database.

    Error: listen EADDRINUSE: address already in use :::3001

    Head to your .env, and change the port number to another number that is not in use.

    MongooseError: The `uri` parameter to `openUri()` must be a string, got "undefined". Make sure the first parameter to `mongoose.connect()` or `mongoose.createConnection()` is a string. 

MongoAPIError: URI must include hostname, domain name, and tld

    Check your .env file and ensure that the first line is correct. You have replaced your password correctly, and that the value is enclosed in " ". The password also does not have any special characters. 

    MongoServerError: bad auth : authentication failed

    Do check that the connection string that you are using in line 1 of .env is correct.
